{"id":"d=origam-topic-3966//p=220dd6cf6dd84414887b4a230362ef4e","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-3966"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["fb199ccbd0d84b55806cd18721119397"],"__file_part":["22ac2c50b97548f4b6681ef69a435925"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["3966"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-setup-a-drop-down-menu/3966"],"title":["How to setup a drop-down menu"],"imagesFound":["17"],"imagesDescribed":["17"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/ddec2ad96aeb23136d7353dd039a3086033856b5.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5f95982a36965be36ea88972590f0cafe19a97f2.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/45cbcc999b3091f7288251cd9b3d8d41663e085b.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6d1aa4e20f7a6b4b056e2beddab716615c2f214c.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4606ba95bfb1c934b16e4b36c606428b8f63812e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8f8a4370cbedc1fafdea529c7e7617a982c275e8.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7a702f2bf443dd8fc5d6ac05b386d2c7dc1814fb.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/9/9fe3e774a1254ca4318b1cf1164ee5ecea028a1f.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/41327d909ec51570ea4deaf15809afc9f78f3a1e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f973ba138cae1e8a5ac2d35bbb7c2f0c02c5bb52.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b1d3fd24c39554b7ad1420e6f963bc9e96293f43.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/1bbe11732aac1070a02c6916449f5aa8e0d1ed87.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b2f74c7556097f3df714eecdd4a2f886af2a328f.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a73a17422b9bfc83672fe21487a451ac105912d4.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f995aa4b859d0cf0b0bdc85251f38ae52fee1678.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a35e6119002b7dd778e2ae0fb1e972a9ded8e019.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a30bebf76ae2f244ae392eed7db25e73e33a8f57.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to setup a drop-down menu\n\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-setup-a-drop-down-menu/3966\n\n@vikter (2025-02-20 09:37:39Z):\n   \n This guide will walk you through the process of creating and setting up a drop-down menu in user screens. \n \n [!success]- Prerequisites for further work \n To follow along, ensure the following prerequisites are met: \n \n  Running database server  \n  Running ORIGAM Server  \n  Project created in ORIGAM Architect  \n  Entities and fields created  \n  Lookup created  \n  User screen created  \n  Running client application in your browser  \n \n Once these prerequisites are set up, log into the client application using the  username and password you created  during the project setup. \n \n A drop-down menu can be created either via a wizard (action) or manually. In both methods, at least two entities need to be created: the main entity, where you will use the drop-down menu to populate one of its fields, and a second entity (auxiliary), which will be used in the drop-down menu to populate the field of the main entity. \n In this example, we will use  Task  (main entity) and two different entities for the drop-down menus -  Priority  and  Status . \n   Drop-down menu with Action \n Drop-down menus can be automatically generated with the  New Screen  Action. To make this work, the following four prerequisites must be met: \n \n The main Entity contains a Field that references the Id of another Entity using  ForeignKey . \n The  DataType  of this Field is set to  Uniqueidentifier , with  DataLength  = 0. \n The auxiliary Entity has a Lookup defined. \n The main Entity has the  DefaultLookup  property set to that Lookup. \n \n In our example, the  Task  entity has two fields -  Priority_Id  and  Status_id . These fields are set up like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/ddec2ad96aeb23136d7353dd039a3086033856b5.png]\nDescription: The image displays a Database Field configuration interface for \u0022Priority_Id.\u0022 It includes sections labeled \u0022Entity Column\u0022 and \u0022Foreign Key.\u0022 Under \u0022Entity Column,\u0022 the entries are: Name (Priority_Id), AllowNulls (True), DataLength (0), DataType (UniqueIdentifier), and DefaultLookup (Priority_Name_GetId). The \u0022Foreign Key\u0022 section lists ForeignKeyEntity (Priority) and ForeignKeyField (Id). The context appears to be related to database schema management, specifically focusing on defining attributes and relationships for the \u0022Priority_Id\u0022 field in a data structure.\n\n\n  \n If everything is correctly set up, the  Create Screen Action  will automatically generate a drop-down menu for your application, such as this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5f95982a36965be36ea88972590f0cafe19a97f2.png]\nDescription: Screen Section: Task interface for a data management system. Visible elements include data source details and properties for the task. In the left panel, labels are: Name, Id, Package, Toolbox, Task, Widgets. The main area includes fields: Description, Assigned to, DueDate, Priority, and Status, with the \u0022Priority\u0022 field highlighted in red. The user can interact with fields through icons for selection, indicating functionality for task assignment and priority setting. No values are provided in the fields, suggesting this is a template setup for managing tasks within a software application.\n\n\n  \n   Manual procedure \n The prerequisites for this method are the same as when using the Action. The only difference is that, when creating your screen manually, you will select the field for which you want to create the drop-down menu from the Toolbox and then assign the  AsCombo  option in  Widgets : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/45cbcc999b3091f7288251cd9b3d8d41663e085b.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface component labeled \u0022Toolbox\u0022 with two tabs: \u0022Task\u0022 and \u0022Widgets.\u0022 Under the \u0022Widgets\u0022 tab, various options are listed, including \u0022\u003CPointer\u003E\u0022, \u0022AsCheckBox\u0022, \u0022AsCombo\u0022, \u0022AsDateBox\u0022, \u0022AsTextBox\u0022, \u0022BlobControl\u0022, \u0022Checklist\u0022, \u0022ColorPicker\u0022, \u0022GroupBox\u0022, \u0022ImageBox\u0022, \u0022Label\u0022, \u0022MultiColumnAdapterFieldWrapp\u0022, \u0022RadioButton\u0022, and \u0022TagInput.\u0022 Each item is represented with a corresponding icon, indicating their function in a graphical user interface design context, likely for building forms or applications. The apparent purpose of this toolbox is to provide developers with ready-to-use UI widgets for application development.\n\n\n","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:49:38"},"vector":[0.001469722,-0.018990165,-0.058893345,0.016342973,-0.017794289,-0.01459019,0.0408315,0.010431061,-0.0004193495,0.025999712,0.021724613,-0.014900036,-0.015996547,0.029880848,0.04453732,0.01667583,0.009765167,0.0069170007,0.03290001,0.038884416,-0.013126591,0.0075574075,0.06615496,0.021622226,0.0009343762,0.03555224,0.013966293,-0.061472777,-0.037401617,-0.014698845,0.012413523,-0.06470993,-0.024660159,-0.04002834,0.0043803207,-0.010417869,-0.008890423,0.006734311,-0.051730342,0.029353958,-0.0172214,0.008833761,-0.007355972,0.0060362476,0.014995228,-0.03430547,-0.0028471155,-0.009803151,-0.0015739711,-0.05574113,-0.06483974,-0.011464562,0.0029635916,-0.00094984396,0.05657045,0.05166708,-0.00